Prospera OS
Governance Evidence Protocol v1.0

File: governance/evidence-protocol-v1.0.md
Status: Stable
Owner: Prospera Governance Council
Category: Governance Specification

──────────────────────────────────

Purpose

This document defines the mandatory evidence, audit, and verification structures
used across all layers of Prospera OS.

The protocol ensures:
• non-repudiation
• traceability
• determinism
• version integrity
• governance enforceability

All systems, engines, and modules must comply with this protocol.
No component may execute without leaving valid evidence.

──────────────────────────────────

Evidence Requirements

All evidence must be:
• immutable
• timestamped
• signed
• pipeline-routed
• hash-anchored in SSOT
• cross-verifiable

Evidence must allow full reconstructability of execution.

──────────────────────────────────

Evidence Structure

Each evidence object must contain the following fields:

3.1 Metadata Block
• evidence_id
• evidence_type
• system
• engine
• version
• timestamp_issued
• source

3.2 Intent Block
• intent_id
• parsed_intent
• classification
• safety_status
• routing_path

3.3 Execution Block
• execution_id
• execution_state_before
• execution_state_after
• pipeline_stage
• engine_action

3.4 Safety Block
• safety_result
• constraints_applied
• safety_reason
• override_if_any

3.5 Governance Block
• governance_policy_enforced
• governance_decision
• violation_flag
• escalation_level

3.6 Hash & Signature Block
• evidence_hash
• parent_hash
• ssot_hash_anchor
• signature
• verification_result

──────────────────────────────────

Evidence Lifecycle

4.1 Creation
Evidence is created automatically by Pipeline Stage 1.

4.2 Validation
Governance validates:
• integrity
• structure
• signatures
• hash consistency

4.3 Writeback
Only validated evidence may be written into SSOT.
Invalid evidence is rejected and flagged.

4.4 Archival
Evidence older than threshold enters immutable archive storage.
No rewrites are allowed.

──────────────────────────────────

Evidence Types

Mandatory standardized types:
• INTENT_EVIDENCE
• SAFETY_EVIDENCE
• EXECUTION_EVIDENCE
• AUTONOMY_EVIDENCE
• DRIFT_EVIDENCE
• VIOLATION_EVIDENCE
• GOVERNANCE_ACTION_EVIDENCE

No new types may be added without governance approval.

──────────────────────────────────

Verification Rules

Evidence must always be verifiable by:
• hash chain validation
• signature match
• pipeline ordering check
• governance rule consistency
• cross-layer reconciliation

Any failure = automatic violation escalation.

──────────────────────────────────

SSOT Anchoring Rules

Each evidence object must be anchored in SSOT with:
• ssot_hash_anchor
• global_execution_counter
• parent-child hash chain

SSOT is the sole truth authority.
If SSOT rejects evidence → execution cannot continue.

──────────────────────────────────

Governance Enforcement

Governance enforces that evidence must:
• precede execution
• match execution state
• match safety constraints
• match routing map
• satisfy version consistency
• contain no missing fields
• contain no unverifiable elements

Governance may halt any subsystem upon evidence failure.

──────────────────────────────────

Prohibited Evidence Conditions

The following evidence conditions are forbidden:
• mutable fields after emission
• gaps in hash chain
• out-of-order timestamps
• missing blocks
• mismatched version tags
• local-only evidence (must go through pipeline)
• unsigned evidence

Violation triggers automatic recovery and backtracking.

──────────────────────────────────

Versioning

v1.0 Initial Evidence Protocol
v1.1 Multi-layer verification expansion
v2.x Distributed cryptographic verification

